## Simple Answer

```
CPU does NOT block itself!

The METHOD blocks the THREAD
by making it WAIT for something

CPU moves on to other threads!
```

---

## The Real Picture

```
Common misconception ❌
───────────────────────
"CPU gets blocked and does nothing"

Reality ✅
──────────
Thread gets blocked → waits for something
CPU leaves that thread → runs other threads
CPU is NEVER truly idle (mostly!)
```

---

## All Situations When a Thread Gets Blocked

---

### 1. Thread.sleep() — Time Based Block

```java
System.out.println("before sleep");
Thread.sleep(5000);   // ← blocks HERE
System.out.println("after sleep");
```

```
What happens:
─────────────
Thread says → "I want to wait 5 seconds"
OS sets a timer for 5 seconds
Thread state → TIMED_WAITING
CPU leaves this thread immediately!
CPU runs other threads...
After 5s → OS wakes thread up
Thread state → RUNNABLE again
```

```
Timeline:
Thread  ████ SLEEP(5s) ░░░░░░░░░░░░░░ ████
CPU     ████ [other threads / work] ░░ ████
             ↑                      ↑
          left thread            came back
```

---

### 2. I/O Operations — Waiting for Data

```java
// Reading a file
FileReader fr = new FileReader("song.mp3");  // ← BLOCKS
fr.read();

// Network call
URL url = new URL("http://api.music.com");
url.openConnection().getInputStream();  // ← BLOCKS

// Database query
ResultSet rs = statement.executeQuery("SELECT * FROM songs"); // ← BLOCKS
```

```
What happens:
─────────────
Thread asks OS → "give me this file/data"
OS sends request to Disk/Network
Thread state → BLOCKED (waiting for data)
CPU leaves this thread!

Speed comparison:
CPU speed  → nanoseconds  (0.000000001s)
RAM speed  → nanoseconds
Disk speed → milliseconds (0.001s)
Network    → seconds

CPU would waste MILLIONS of cycles waiting!
So CPU runs other threads instead
```

```
Timeline:
Thread  ████ ░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░ ████
             waiting for disk/network
CPU     ████ [running other threads] ████
```

---

### 3. synchronized Block — Lock Waiting

```java
synchronized(this) {   // ← BLOCKS if another thread holds lock
    counter++;
}
```

```
What happens:
─────────────
Thread 1 → holds the lock → running
Thread 2 → tries to enter synchronized block
         → lock already taken!
         → Thread 2 state → BLOCKED
         → CPU leaves Thread 2
         → Thread 1 finishes → releases lock
         → Thread 2 gets lock → RUNNABLE again
```

```
Timeline:
Thread 1  ████ [locked zone] 🔓 ░░░
Thread 2  ░░░░ ⏳waiting...  ░░ ████
               ↑ blocked here
```

